{"type":"message","id":"a144a451","parentId":"3d584204","timestamp":"2026-04-23T05:13:31.714Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mình đang ở đúng phần lõi nhất: **chuẩn hóa taxonomy và role map**. Đây là bước quan trọng vì nếu phân loại agent không chặt thì các phần sau như workflow, governance, metrics sẽ bị lệch hết."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_AT9Nh8V63nS6f61ZBTT0RQS0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/01-multi-agent-overview.md","content":"# Multi-Agent Ecosystem Overview\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the purpose, structure, and operating intent of the current multi-agent ecosystem. It is designed to serve as the top-level entry point for management and technical stakeholders before they review lower-level documentation such as taxonomy, workflows, governance, and metrics.\n\n## Executive Summary\nThe current ecosystem is not a single assistant with ad hoc specialist prompts. It has evolved into a layered multi-agent operating model with clear evidence of specialization across product, engineering, quality, security, design, content, research, and operations.\n\nAt a high level, the ecosystem already demonstrates three important characteristics:\n1. **Central orchestration exists** through a control layer centered around the master orchestrator.\n2. **Capability specialization exists** through reusable expert agents.\n3. **Domain specialization exists** through AHV DTLX-specific agents aligned to a real project context.\n\nHowever, the ecosystem is currently stronger in **agent availability** than in **agent operating standardization**. The next maturity step is to formalize taxonomy, workflows, role boundaries, governance, metrics, and reusable documentation standards.\n\n## Why this ecosystem matters\nThe ecosystem creates leverage by allowing complex tasks to be decomposed into specialist roles instead of forcing all work through a single generalist interaction pattern. This improves:\n- quality of outputs\n- clarity of responsibility\n- reuse across projects\n- scalability of internal AI operations\n- potential for measurable productivity gains\n\n## Current operating model\nThe ecosystem currently functions through a layered structure:\n\n### 1. Control Layer\nThe control layer is responsible for intake, clarification, task routing, orchestration, and final synthesis.\n\nTypical responsibilities:\n- clarify ambiguous requests\n- decide whether to route to a specialist\n- coordinate multi-step execution\n- consolidate outputs into a final response or deliverable\n- enforce workflow rules and confirmation gates\n\nPrimary examples:\n- `master-orchestrator`\n- `prompt-optimizer` (as an intake and refinement gate)\n- potentially planner-like orchestration support depending on task type\n\n### 2. Reusable Capability Layer\nThis layer contains reusable specialist agents that are not tied to one specific project. These agents provide expert capability in areas such as:\n- frontend\n- backend\n- QA\n- architecture\n- security\n- code review\n- database design\n- content strategy\n- market intelligence\n- performance optimization\n- documentation lookup\n- UX/UI and design systems\n\nThese agents are intended to be portable across projects and should ultimately become the backbone of a reusable internal agent platform.\n\n### 3. Domain-Specific Layer\nThis layer contains project-centered variants for the AHV DTLX ecosystem. These agents encode domain context, project assumptions, deliverable structure, and workflow expectations for a specific operational environment.\n\nTypical examples include:\n- `ahv-dtlx-fe`\n- `ahv-dtlx-be`\n- `ahv-dtlx-review`\n- `ahv-dtlx-architect`\n- `ahv-dtlx-qa`\n- `ahv-dtlx-db-schema`\n- `ahv-dtlx-devops`\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-design`\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-ux`\n\nThese agents are the bridge between reusable expert capabilities and real project delivery.\n\n## Current maturity assessment\nThe ecosystem appears to be at an intermediate maturity stage:\n\n### Strengths\n- strong breadth of specialization\n- visible intent toward orchestration rather than isolated prompting\n- domain-specific operational lanes already created\n- documentation exists for many agents, including role, outputs, and workspace structure in stronger examples\n\n### Weaknesses\n- documentation quality is inconsistent across agents\n- role boundaries are not yet formalized at system level\n- workflow handoffs are implied rather than standardized\n- governance and escalation policies are fragmented\n- KPI and adoption measurement are not yet institutionalized\n- reuse strategy is visible but not explicitly documented\n\n## Strategic recommendation\nThe next strategic step is not to create many more agents. It is to make the current ecosystem easier to understand, operate, measure, and scale.\n\nThat means focusing on:\n- taxonomy\n- orchestration design\n- standard workflows\n- role contracts\n- governance\n- metrics\n- case studies\n- lifecycle management\n\n## Required documentation set\nTo operationalize the ecosystem as a durable internal capability, the following document set is required:\n1. Overview\n2. Taxonomy and inventory\n3. Orchestration architecture\n4. Standard workflows\n5. Agent specification framework\n6. Governance and operating model\n7. Metrics and adoption model\n8. Gap analysis and roadmap\n9. Applied case studies\n\n## Intended audiences\n### Management audience\nNeeds:\n- what the ecosystem is\n- why it matters\n- what value it creates\n- what gaps remain\n- what maturity level it has reached\n\n### Technical audience\nNeeds:\n- how agents are classified\n- how orchestration works\n- how handoff works\n- how agents should be documented\n- how governance and metrics are defined\n\n## Definition of success\nThis documentation effort will be considered successful when:\n- every major agent class is classified and explained\n- workflow patterns are explicit and repeatable\n- the difference between reusable and project-specific agents is formalized\n- the system can be explained to leadership and technical contributors without ambiguity\n- the ecosystem can be extended without increasing disorder\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_mqnjhUgdVkLCHXH2HnFGEbaZ","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/02-agent-taxonomy-and-inventory.md","content":"# Agent Taxonomy and Inventory\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the classification model for the current multi-agent ecosystem and provides the basis for architecture, governance, workflow design, and future scaling.\n\n## Taxonomy Model\nThe current ecosystem should be classified into four primary layers.\n\n## Layer 1 — Control Agents\nThese agents are responsible for intake, clarification, orchestration, routing, and consolidation.\n\n### Characteristics\n- interact closest to the user or parent request\n- decide whether specialist delegation is needed\n- manage sequencing and synthesis\n- enforce confirmation and workflow gates\n\n### Current examples\n- `master-orchestrator`\n- `prompt-optimizer`\n- `planner` (where used as coordination support)\n- `harness-optimizer` (when operating as an orchestration optimization control role)\n\n### Notes\nThis layer is strategically critical. It should remain small, highly reliable, and tightly governed.\n\n## Layer 2 — Reusable Capability Agents\nThese agents provide portable specialist expertise that should be reusable across multiple projects.\n\n### Capability clusters\n#### Engineering\n- `senior-frontend`\n- `senior-backend`\n- `senior-architect`\n- `typescript-reviewer`\n- `code-reviewer`\n- `clean-code`\n- `coding-standards`\n- `refactor-cleaner`\n\n#### Quality and Security\n- `senior-qa`\n- `security-reviewer`\n- `senior-security`\n- `performance-optimizer`\n- `database-reviewer`\n- `database-schema-designer`\n\n#### Product, Research, and Strategy\n- `agile-product-owner`\n- `product-strategy`\n- `market-intelligence`\n- `deep-research`\n\n#### Content and Communication\n- `content-engine`\n- `content-strategy`\n- `article-writing`\n- `documentation-lookup`\n- `ai-seo`\n- `seo-audit`\n\n#### Design and Experience\n- `ui-design-system`\n- `ui-ux-pro-max`\n- `epic-design`\n- `stitch-design`\n- `stitch-loop`\n- `playwright-pro`\n- `shadcn-expert`\n\n#### Operational / Utility\n- `realistic-seeder`\n- `planner`\n- `harness-optimizer`\n\n### Notes\nThese agents should become the canonical reusable catalog for future projects.\n\n## Layer 3 — Domain-Specific Agents\nThese agents are tuned for the AHV DTLX domain and should be considered project-aligned specialist variants rather than universal agents.\n\n### Product / Planning\n- `ahv-dtlx-agile`\n- `ahv-dtlx-epic`\n- `ahv-dtlx-product-strategy`\n- `ahv-dtlx-market`\n\n### Engineering\n- `ahv-dtlx-fe`\n- `ahv-dtlx-be`\n- `ahv-dtlx-architect`\n- `ahv-dtlx-db-schema`\n- `ahv-dtlx-devops`\n- `ahv-dtlx-standards`\n- `ahv-dtlx-clean`\n- `ahv-dtlx-review`\n- `ahv-dtlx-perf`\n- `ahv-dtlx-harness`\n\n### Quality / Security\n- `ahv-dtlx-qa`\n- `ahv-dtlx-security`\n- `ahv-dtlx-senior-security`\n- `ahv-dtlx-playwright`\n\n### Design / UX\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-design`\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-ux`\n- `ahv-dtlx-shadcn`\n- `ahv-dtlx-stitch`\n\n### Content / Documentation / Discovery\n- `ahv-dtlx-docs`\n- `ahv-dtlx-content-engine`\n- `ahv-dtlx-content-strategy`\n- `ahv-dtlx-seo`\n- `ahv-dtlx-prompt`\n\n### Notes\nThis layer gives the ecosystem project relevance, but it also introduces overlap risk if role boundaries are not clearly documented.\n\n## Layer 4 — Temporary or Situation-Specific Agents\nThis layer should include agents created for a temporary initiative, migration, experiment, or narrow scope. Some agents may move in or out of this class over time.\n\n### Observed pattern\nThe current ecosystem does not yet document this class formally, even though the need clearly exists.\n\n### Why formalizing this layer matters\nWithout a temporary-agent classification, the ecosystem tends to accumulate agents without a retirement model, which increases confusion and maintenance overhead.\n\n## Classification principles\nTo reduce future ambiguity, each agent should explicitly declare:\n1. **Layer**\n2. **Capability class**\n3. **Primary owner role**\n4. **Reusable or project-specific status**\n5. **Expected inputs**\n6. **Expected outputs**\n7. **Escalation targets**\n8. **Lifecycle status** — draft / active / limited / deprecated\n\n## Inventory observations\n### Observation 1 — Strong coverage\nThe ecosystem already covers most major internal operating functions needed for AI-assisted delivery.\n\n### Observation 2 — Uneven standardization\nSome agents have strong AGENTS.md definitions with role, outputs, and workflow. Others still rely mostly on generic bootstrap instructions.\n\n### Observation 3 — Overlap risk\nSeveral areas have both generic and domain-specific variants but no authoritative boundary definition. This creates confusion about when to use the reusable agent versus the AHV DTLX-specific variant.\n\n### Observation 4 — Missing authoritative registry\nThere is no single source of truth listing all agents, their status, their maturity, and when they should be used.\n\n## Recommended inventory fields\nA formal registry should include at minimum:\n- Agent Name\n- Layer\n- Capability Cluster\n- Scope\n- Reusable / Domain / Temporary\n- Primary Purpose\n- Typical Inputs\n- Typical Outputs\n- Escalates To\n- Depends On\n- Maturity Level\n- Documentation Quality\n- Lifecycle Status\n\n## Immediate recommendations\n1. create a canonical agent registry\n2. assign each agent to one taxonomy layer\n3. define boundary rules between reusable and domain-specific agents\n4. add lifecycle status to every agent\n5. standardize AGENTS.md structure across the ecosystem\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9Y8AFKhDd8YErWcij8UmKhV2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"git -C /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator status --short docs | sed -n '1,120p'","yieldMs":1000,"timeout":30}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-TroLy","usage":{"input":2609,"output":2777,"cacheRead":92544,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97930,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776921157802,"responseId":"1776921160215"}}
