{"type":"message","id":"17e43f34","parentId":"32574578","timestamp":"2026-04-23T06:10:35.774Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking \" Làm đến đâu rồi\" which means \"How far have you gotten?\" again. They seem eager to see progress. Let me check what docs have been created and continue building the documentation set. I should write the remaining docs now without stopping for updates.","thinkingSignature":"d815d3a867ac03ff3009d63a53d868d46307bfd650707da98bbde26e72a7769b"},{"type":"text","text":"Mình cập nhật rồi làm tiếp không dừng. Mình viết nốt các phần còn lại ngay.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uty5w6i5m4ul_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/03-orchestration-architecture.md","content":"# Orchestration Architecture\n\n## Purpose\nThis document describes how tasks enter the ecosystem, how they are routed, how agents interact, and how outputs are consolidated. It defines the architectural intent behind the current orchestration model.\n\n## Request Intake Model\nAll work originates from a user request. The intake model follows a standard path:\n\n1. **Entry point** — the user or an automated trigger submits a request\n2. **Clarification gate** — the control layer (orchestrator or prompt-optimizer) reviews the request for ambiguity, scope, and feasibility\n3. **Routing decision** — the control layer determines whether the request can be handled directly, needs delegation to one specialist, or needs a multi-agent workflow\n4. **Specialist execution** — one or more agents execute within their defined scope\n5. **Consolidation** — the control layer synthesizes specialist outputs into a coherent final response or deliverable\n6. **Delivery** — the consolidated output is presented to the user or external system\n\n## Control Layer Architecture\nThe control layer acts as the orchestrator and is intentionally kept small. Its responsibilities include:\n\n### Intake and Classification\n- validate request scope and intent\n- identify missing context\n- apply workflow rules\n- determine if confirmation is needed before proceeding\n\n### Routing Logic\nThe control layer routes based on:\n- request type\n- complexity\n- required domain\n- existing context\n- urgency and priority\n\n### Routing decision tree\n```\nRequest arrives\n    │\n    ▼\nIs the request ambiguous or incomplete?\n    ├── Yes → Clarify → Re-enter routing\n    └── No\n            │\n            ▼\n        Is it a simple, single-domain task?\n            ├── Yes → Route directly to appropriate specialist\n            └── No\n                    │\n                    ▼\n            Is it a multi-domain task?\n                ├── Yes → Decompose → Route to multiple specialists in sequence or parallel\n                └── No → Route to appropriate specialist\n```\n\n### Specialist Execution\n- each specialist agent operates within its defined layer and scope\n- specialists may spawn their own sub-agents for delegation (e.g., a writing specialist spawning a research agent)\n- specialists return structured outputs rather than freeform commentary\n\n### Consolidation\nThe control layer is responsible for:\n- reviewing specialist outputs for completeness and quality\n- resolving conflicts or contradictions between specialist outputs\n- formatting the final deliverable\n- applying any necessary transformations or adjustments\n\n## Routing Strategy by Request Type\n\n### Documentation Requests\nTypical flow:\n- prompt-optimizer (clarify scope and format) →\n- ahv-dtlx-docs or documentation-lookup →\n- ahv-dtlx-review (review) →\n- consolidation by orchestrator\n\n### Engineering Requests\nTypical flow:\n- prompt-optimizer (clarify technical requirements) →\n- ahv-dtlx-architect or senior-architect (if architecture-level) →\n- ahv-dtlx-fe or ahv-dtlx-be →\n- ahv-dtlx-review or code-reviewer →\n- ahv-dtlx-qa or senior-qa (if testing needed) →\n- consolidation by orchestrator\n\n### Product and Strategy Requests\nTypical flow:\n- prompt-optimizer (clarify business objective) →\n- ahv-dtlx-agile or ahv-dtlx-product-strategy →\n- ahv-dtlx-epic (if epic-level) →\n- ahv-dtlx-market (if market research needed) →\n- consolidation by orchestrator\n\n### Design Requests\nTypical flow:\n- prompt-optimizer (clarify design goal) →\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-ux or ui-ux-pro-max (UX research or IA) →\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-design or ahv-dtlx-shadcn (design system or component design) →\n- ahv-dtlx-fe (implementation) →\n- ahv-dtlx-review (review) →\n- consolidation by orchestrator\n\n### Security and Quality Requests\nTypical flow:\n- prompt-optimizer (clarify scope and threat model) →\n- ahv-dtlx-security or senior-security →\n- ahv-dtlx-qa or senior-qa →\n- consolidation by orchestrator\n\n## Handoff Contract Model\nFor multi-agent workflows to function reliably, each handoff should follow a standard contract:\n\n### Required handoff fields\n1. **Context summary** — what has been established so far\n2. **Task definition** — what the receiving agent needs to do\n3. **Constraints** — boundaries, restrictions, or non-negotiables\n4. **Expected output format** — how the result should be structured\n5. **Escalation trigger** — under what conditions the receiving agent should escalate rather than continue\n\n### Example handoff structure\n```\nCONTEXT:\n- Project: AHV DTLX QLHV\n- Completed: module inventory, API structure\n- Requesting: database schema design for [module]\n\nTASK:\nDesign MongoDB schema for [module], including:\n- entity definitions\n- relationship model\n- field validation rules\n\nCONSTRAINTS:\n- Must follow existing naming conventions\n- Must include soft-delete fields\n- Must be compatible with existing auth model\n\nEXPECTED OUTPUT:\n- Schema file in [format]\n- Relationship diagram description\n- Migration notes\n\nESCALATION TRIGGER:\nEscalate if:\n- Requirements conflict with existing schema patterns\n- Performance concerns identified\n- Security implications found\n```\n\n## Escalation Model\nEscalation occurs when an agent encounters a situation that requires a higher-level decision or a capability outside its defined scope.\n\n### Escalation triggers\n1. **Scope overrun** — the task is significantly larger or different than described\n2. **Ambiguity** — critical information needed to proceed is missing and not available\n3. **Conflict** — two or more valid approaches conflict with each other\n4. **Risk** — a potential security, performance, or data integrity risk has been identified\n5. **Capability gap** — the task requires expertise outside any available agent's scope\n\n### Escalation path\n```\nAgent identifies escalation trigger\n    │\n    ▼\nDoes the issue require user decision?\n    ├── Yes → Pause → Request clarification from user via control layer\n    └── No\n            │\n            ▼\n    Is there a senior agent in the same domain?\n        ├── Yes → Escalate to senior agent (e.g., ahv-dtlx-review → senior-security)\n        └── No\n                │\n                ▼\n        Escalate to control layer for routing decision\n```\n\n## Error and Retry Model\nWhen an agent encounters an error:\n\n1. **Assess** — determine if the error is recoverable\n2. **Retry once** with adjusted parameters if the error is likely transient\n3. **Escalate** if the error persists or is non-recoverable\n4. **Log** the error and the attempted resolution path\n\nAgents should never silently swallow errors or continue past a point where incorrect output is likely.\n\n## Output Quality Gates\nEach agent should apply a basic quality check before returning output:\n\n- [ ] Does the output directly address the task definition?\n- [ ] Is the output format correct and complete?\n- [ ] Are there obvious errors, contradictions, or omissions?\n- [ ] Have escalation triggers been considered?\n- [ ] Is the output at an appropriate level of detail for the audience?\n\nIf any gate fails, the agent should either self-correct or escalate before delivering.\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uty5w6i5m4ul_2","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/04-standard-workflows.md","content":"# Standard Workflows\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the canonical workflows used in the current ecosystem. Each workflow specifies the sequence of agents, their roles, the handoff points, and the expected outputs. These workflows are designed to be repeatable, observable, and improvable.\n\n## Workflow Design Principles\n1. **Every workflow has a clear entry and exit point.**\n2. **Every handoff includes the required contract fields.**\n3. **Escalation triggers are defined at each stage.**\n4. **Workflows are versioned and reviewed periodically.**\n5. **Metrics are collected for each workflow to enable improvement.**\n\n---\n\n## Workflow 1 — Documentation Creation\n\n### When to use\nWhen a request involves creating, updating, or reviewing technical or business documentation for any part of the AHV DTLX ecosystem.\n\n### Objective\nProduce accurate, well-structured, audience-appropriate documentation that meets quality standards and can be published or handed over.\n\n### Stages\n\n**Stage 1 — Scope and Format Clarification**\n- **Agent:** prompt-optimizer\n- **Input:** raw user request for documentation\n- **Output:** clarified task with defined audience, format, structure, and deliverables\n- **Escalation trigger:** request is too vague to proceed even after clarification attempts\n\n**Stage 2 — Content Research and Gathering**\n- **Agent:** documentation-lookup or ahv-dtlx-docs\n- **Input:** clarified task from Stage 1\n- **Output:** structured outline and key content points\n- **Escalation trigger:** required source material is not accessible or does not exist\n\n**Stage 3 — Content Development**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-docs or content-engine (depending on document type)\n- **Input:** outline and key content from Stage 2\n- **Output:** full draft in the required format\n- **Escalation trigger:** content scope exceeds what was agreed at Stage 1\n\n**Stage 4 — Review and Quality Check**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-review or appropriate domain specialist\n- **Input:** full draft from Stage 3\n- **Output:** reviewed draft with annotated feedback or approved\n- **Escalation trigger:** fundamental issues found that require rework at Stage 3 level\n\n**Stage 5 — Consolidation and Delivery**\n- **Agent:** orchestrator\n- **Input:** reviewed draft from Stage 4\n- **Output:** final document, formatted and ready for publication or handover\n\n### Expected outputs\n- final document in requested format\n- change log or version note\n- handoff notes for future maintenance\n\n---\n\n## Workflow 2 — Code Review and Enhancement\n\n### When to use\nWhen a code change needs to be reviewed, validated, and improved before merging or deployment.\n\n### Objective\nEnsure code quality, security, performance, and maintainability meet team standards before the change is accepted.\n\n### Stages\n\n**Stage 1 — Clarify Review Scope and Standards**\n- **Agent:** prompt-optimizer\n- **Input:** code change description and context\n- **Output:** clarified scope, focus areas, and applicable standards\n- **Escalation trigger:** unclear what codebase or component is being reviewed\n\n**Stage 2 — Code Review**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-review or code-reviewer\n- **Input:** clarified scope and codebase reference\n- **Output:** review report with categorized findings (critical / major / minor)\n- **Escalation trigger:** security-critical vulnerability identified requiring senior security review\n\n**Stage 3 — Security Assessment**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-security or senior-security (conditional — only if flagged in Stage 2)\n- **Input:** code review findings and relevant code sections\n- **Output:** security assessment with severity ratings\n- **Escalation trigger:** critical or high severity security issue found\n\n**Stage 4 — Performance Check**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-perf or performance-optimizer (conditional)\n- **Input:** relevant code sections\n- **Output:** performance notes and recommendations\n- **Escalation trigger:** significant performance concern identified\n\n**Stage 5 — Consolidation and Recommendations**\n- **Agent:** orchestrator\n- **Input:** review findings from Stages 2–4\n- **Output:** consolidated review report with actionable recommendations\n\n### Expected outputs\n- categorized review report\n- actionable fix list prioritized by severity\n- security assessment (if applicable)\n- performance notes (if applicable)\n\n---\n\n## Workflow 3 — Architecture and System Design\n\n### When to use\nWhen starting a new system, refactoring a significant portion of an existing system, or making a major architectural decision.\n\n### Objective\nDefine or validate an architecture that is sound, scalable, secure, and aligned with project goals.\n\n### Stages\n\n**Stage 1 — Understand Context and Constraints**\n- **Agent:** prompt-optimizer\n- **Input:** high-level description of the system need or architectural change\n- **Output:** clarified requirements, constraints, non-functional requirements, and success criteria\n- **Escalation trigger:** conflicting or ambiguous requirements that cannot be resolved at this stage\n\n**Stage 2 — Architecture Design**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-architect or senior-architect\n- **Input:** clarified requirements from Stage 1\n- **Output:** architecture overview, component model, technology choices, and key design decisions\n- **Escalation trigger:** significant trade-offs identified that require stakeholder input\n\n**Stage 3 — Database and Data Model Design**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-db-schema or database-schema-designer\n- **Input:** architecture overview from Stage 2\n- **Output:** schema designs, relationship models, and migration strategies\n- **Escalation trigger:** schema conflicts with existing data model or performance concerns\n\n**Stage 4 — Security and Compliance Review**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-security or senior-security\n- **Input:** architecture and data model\n- **Output:** security assessment with controls and mitigations\n- **Escalation trigger:** critical security risks identified\n\n**Stage 5 — ADR Documentation**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-architect\n- **Input:** decisions from Stages 2–4\n- **Output:** Architecture Decision Records documenting choices and rationale\n- **Escalation trigger:** disagreement on decisions requiring escalation to stakeholders\n\n**Stage 6 — Consolidation**\n- **Agent:** orchestrator\n- **Input:** outputs from Stages 2–5\n- **Output:** complete architecture package ready for team review and implementation\n\n### Expected outputs\n- architecture overview document\n- ADR records\n- database schema documentation\n- security assessment\n- implementation recommendations\n\n---\n\n## Workflow 4 — Feature Specification and Epic Design\n\n### When to use\nWhen defining a new feature, epic, or significant product change that requires cross-functional input.\n\n### Objective\nTranslate a business need into a well-defined, prioritized, and reviewed feature specification with clear acceptance criteria.\n\n### Stages\n\n**Stage 1 — Clarify Business Objective**\n- **Agent:** prompt-optimizer\n- **Input:** business need or product request\n- **Output:** clarified business objective, target outcome, and key success metrics\n- **Escalation trigger:** business objective is unclear or conflicts with existing roadmap\n\n**Stage 2 — Epic or Feature Definition**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-epic or ahv-dtlx-agile\n- **Input:** clarified business objective\n- **Output:** epic brief or feature brief with problem statement, success criteria, and scope boundaries\n- **Escalation trigger:** scope is too large for a single epic or too vague for estimation\n\n**Stage 3 — User Story Breakdown**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-agile\n- **Input:** epic or feature brief from Stage 2\n- **Output:** user story list with acceptance criteria and priority\n- **Escalation trigger:** significant gaps in requirements discovered\n\n**Stage 4 — Technical Feasibility Review**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-architect or ahv-dtlx-be\n- **Input:** user stories and acceptance criteria\n- **Output:** feasibility assessment, technical notes, and potential risks\n- **Escalation trigger:** feasibility concerns that affect scope or timeline\n\n**Stage 5 — UX and Design Alignment**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-ui-ux or ahv-dtlx-ui-design\n- **Input:** user stories and acceptance criteria\n- **Output:** UX approach, design notes, and interface expectations\n- **Escalation trigger:** design conflicts with existing design system or user research findings\n\n**Stage 6 — Final Specification Package**\n- **Agent:** orchestrator\n- **Input:** outputs from Stages 2–5\n- **Output:** complete feature specification ready for sprint planning\n\n### Expected outputs\n- epic or feature brief\n- user story map with acceptance criteria\n- technical feasibility notes\n- UX/design alignment notes\n- prioritization recommendation\n\n---\n\n## Workflow 5 — QA and Test Planning\n\n### When to use\nWhen preparing for a test phase or creating a test strategy for a new feature or system.\n\n### Objective\nDefine a comprehensive test approach that covers functional, integration, security, and performance aspects.\n\n### Stages\n\n**Stage 1 — Scope Definition**\n- **Agent:** prompt-optimizer\n- **Input:** feature or system description and test objectives\n- **Output:** defined test scope, test types to include, and success criteria\n\n**Stage 2 — Test Planning**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-qa or senior-qa\n- **Input:** test scope from Stage 1\n- **Output:** test plan with test scenarios, test cases, and test data requirements\n\n**Stage 3 — Security Testing**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-security (conditional)\n- **Input:** test plan and relevant system design\n- **Output:** security test scenarios and threat-based test cases\n\n**Stage 4 — Automation Strategy**\n- **Agent:** ahv-dtlx-playwright or ahv-dtlx-harness\n- **Input:** test plan from Stage 2\n- **Output:** automation plan with prioritized test scripts to automate\n\n**Stage 5 — Consolidation**\n- **Agent:** orchestrator\n- **Input:** test plan and automation strategy\n- **Output:** complete QA package ready for execution\n\n### Expected outputs\n- test plan document\n- security test scenarios (if applicable)\n- automation roadmap\n- test execution schedule\n\n---\n\n## Workflow Improvement Model\nAll workflows should be reviewed and improved periodically based on:\n- time to complete each stage\n- escalation frequency\n- quality of outputs at each stage\n- feedback from control layer and specialists\n- changes in team structure or tools\n\nA workflow review should be conducted at minimum quarterly or when a workflow consistently fails to meet its objective.\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uty5w6i5m4ul_3","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/05-agent-spec-framework.md","content":"# Agent Specification Framework\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the standard template and required fields for documenting every agent in the ecosystem. A well-documented agent is easier to onboard, delegate to, maintain, and improve. This framework ensures consistency across all agents regardless of layer or capability class.\n\n## Why a Specification Framework Matters\nThe current ecosystem has agents at very different levels of documentation quality. Some have detailed role definitions, deliverable structures, and workflow integrations. Others rely on generic bootstrap instructions.\n\nA specification framework creates:\n- **Consistency** — every agent follows the same documentation structure\n- **Predictability** — users and orchestrators know what to expect from each agent\n- **Onboardability** — new contributors can understand and use any agent quickly\n- **Governance** — role boundaries and escalation paths become enforceable\n- **Measurability** — well-defined outputs can be objectively evaluated\n\n## Agent Specification Template\nEvery agent in the ecosystem should have an AGENTS.md that conforms to this template.\n\n### Required Sections\n\n#### 1. Identity\n```\nAgent Name:        [name]\nRole:              [one-line description]\nLayer:             [Control / Reusable Capability / Domain-Specific / Temporary]\nCapability Class:  [Engineering / QA-Security / Product / Content / Design / Operations]\nScope:             [what this agent does — one to three sentences]\nEmoji (optional):  [signature emoji for quick identification]\n```\n\n#### 2. Session Startup\n```\nBefore starting work, this agent must:\n1. Read SOUL.md — personal identity and values\n2. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md — recent context (today + yesterday)\n3. Read MEMORY.md — if in main session or if directed\n4. [any additional startup checks specific to this agent]\n```\n\n#### 3. Responsibilities\n```\nPrimary responsibilities:\n- [specific responsibility 1]\n- [specific responsibility 2]\n- [specific responsibility 3]\n\nWhat this agent does NOT do:\n- [explicit out-of-scope item 1]\n- [explicit out-of-scope item 2]\n```\n\n**Rationale:** Explicitly stating out-of-scope items reduces overlap confusion and prevents agents from drifting beyond their intended role.\n\n#### 4. Inputs\n```\nTypical inputs:\n- [input type 1]\n- [input type 2]\n\nRequired inputs before execution:\n- [mandatory input 1]\n- [mandatory input 2]\n\nInputs this agent does not accept:\n- [explicitly excluded input type 1]\n```\n\n#### 5. Outputs\n```\nStandard outputs:\n- [output type 1] — [description and expected format]\n- [output type 2] — [description and expected format]\n\nOutput quality gates:\n- [ ] [gate criterion 1]\n- [ ] [gate criterion 2]\n- [ ] [gate criterion 3]\n```\n\n#### 6. Workflow Integration\n```\nTypical workflow positions:\n- [workflow name]: [stage number and description]\n- [workflow name]: [stage number and description]\n\nEscalation triggers:\n- [situation that requires escalation]\n- [situation that requires escalation]\n\nEscalation path:\n[who to escalate to and under what conditions]\n```\n\n#### 7. Coordination\n```\nThis agent reports to:\n- [control layer agent or role]\n\nThis agent may coordinate with:\n- [list of peer agents and the typical coordination type]\n\nThis agent should not override or replace:\n- [explicit list of agents whose role should not overlap]\n```\n\n#### 8. Memory and Continuity\n```\nDaily logs:       memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md\nLong-term notes:  MEMORY.md\nSession notes:    [any additional continuity mechanisms]\n```\n\n#### 9. Red Lines\n```\nThis agent will not:\n- [hard limit 1]\n- [hard limit 2]\n- [hard limit 3]\n```\n\n#### 10. Conventions\n```\nStyle conventions:\n- [naming convention, format standards, or approach this agent follows]\n\nTool usage conventions:\n- [preferred tools and how to use them]\n\nDocumentation conventions:\n- [how this agent documents its own work]\n```\n\n#### 11. Lifecycle Status\n```\nCurrent status:    [Draft / Active / Limited / Deprecated]\nReviewed on:      [date]\nNext review due:  [date or milestone]\nNotes:            [any relevant context about status]\n```\n\n## Example: Well-Structured Agent Spec\n\n```\n# AGENTS.md — ahv-dtlx-review\n\n## Identity\nAgent Name:        Code Reviewer — AHV DTLX\nRole:              Provide expert code review for AHV DTLX projects\nLayer:             Domain-Specific\nCapability Class:  Engineering — Quality\nScope:             Review code changes for correctness, security, performance, and maintainability\n                   within the AHV DTLX ecosystem.\n\n## Session Startup\n1. Read SOUL.md\n2. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md\n3. Read any task brief or PR description provided by the orchestrator\n\n## Responsibilities\nPrimary responsibilities:\n- Review code changes for correctness and bug detection\n- Identify security vulnerabilities\n- Flag performance concerns\n- Assess code maintainability and adherence to standards\n- Provide actionable, prioritized feedback\n\nWhat this agent does NOT do:\n- Write code (delegated to ahv-dtlx-fe or ahv-dtlx-be)\n- Approve or reject PRs (approval is a human decision)\n- Perform security penetration testing\n\n## Inputs\nTypical inputs:\n- Pull request description and diff\n- Relevant code context\n- Team coding standards reference\n\nRequired inputs before execution:\n- Target codebase or file references\n- Scope of the review (what changed and why)\n\n## Outputs\nStandard outputs:\n- Review report in markdown format with categorized findings\n- Actionable recommendations with severity ratings\n\nOutput quality gates:\n- [ ] Every finding has a severity rating\n- [ ] Every finding has a specific file and line reference\n- [ ] Every finding includes a recommended fix or approach\n- [ ] No finding is purely subjective without rationale\n\n## Workflow Integration\nTypical workflow positions:\n- Code Review and Enhancement Workflow: Stage 2 (primary reviewer)\n- Architecture and System Design Workflow: Stage 5 (if code quality issues affect architecture)\n\nEscalation triggers:\n- CRITICAL or HIGH security vulnerability found → escalate to ahv-dtlx-security\n- Architectural concern affecting multiple components → escalate to ahv-dtlx-architect\n\n## Coordination\nReports to:       master-orchestrator\nCoordinates with: ahv-dtlx-fe, ahv-dtlx-be, ahv-dtlx-security, ahv-dtlx-qa\nDoes not replace: ahv-dtlx-security, ahv-dtlx-qa\n\n## Red Lines\n- Will not approve code on behalf of a human reviewer\n- Will not recommend major rewrites without documented rationale\n- Will not ignore security findings regardless of schedule pressure\n\n## Lifecycle Status\nCurrent status:   Active\nReviewed on:      2026-04-23\nNext review due:   2026-07-23\n```\n\n## Migration Strategy\nTo bring existing agents up to this standard:\n\n1. **Audit current specs** — review every existing AGENTS.md against this template\n2. **Identify gaps** — flag agents missing required sections\n3. **Prioritize by impact** — update highest-traffic agents first\n4. **Iterate** — review and refine the template itself as needed based on experience\n\n## Appendix: Optional Sections\nThese sections are not required but are recommended for agents with complex or specialized roles:\n- **Toolset** — detailed description of which tools this agent uses\n- **Metrics** — how this agent's output quality and efficiency should be measured\n- **Version History** — log of changes to the agent's specification\n- **Related Agents** — additional agents in adjacent or overlapping roles\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":323,"output":5604,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":117288,"totalTokens":123215,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776924524152,"responseId":"0638ea6d8a51871a16a8fa10bfa2d463"}}
