{"type":"message","id":"4bc295eb","parentId":"46c52ebc","timestamp":"2026-04-23T06:59:49.728Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so now I have the accurate numbers:\n- **38 generic/system agents** (not prefixed with ahv-dtlx-)\n- **27 ahv-dtlx- prefixed agents** (project-specific sessions for DTLX project)\n- **Total: 65 agents**\n\nThe ahv-dtlx agents are project sessions for DTLX, so the user is right that the total is ~40 if we only count the system/generic agents. But the 27 ahv-dtlx agents are also real and functional agents.\n\nLet me update the docs to:\n1. Correct the numbers\n\n\n2. Clarify the distinction between generic agents and project-specific DTLX sessions\n3. Adjust the taxonomy accordingly\n\nThe core issue is that the ahv-dtlx agents represent dedicated sessions tied to the DTLX project, while the generic agents make up the system's backbone. I should structure the documentation to reflect both categories accurately, showing how the generic layer provides reusable capabilities and the DTLX layer adds project-specific context. Now I'll update the key docs.","thinkingSignature":"cc5c5c62edb098bccd0fcfbe1da7855b767d247d66f718102642d45ae34af76e"},{"type":"text","text":"�ếm chính xác rồi. Cập nhật lại tài liệu ngay.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_42ndvo73w5lg_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/02-agent-taxonomy-and-inventory.md","edits":[{"oldText":"## Current inventory snapshot\n\n### Observed ecosystem shape\nThe current ecosystem is composed of two overlapping layers:\n\n1. **Generic reusable agents**\n   - prompt-optimizer\n   - planner\n   - senior-frontend\n   - senior-backend\n   - senior-qa\n   - senior-architect\n   - senior-security\n   - code-reviewer\n   - clean-code\n   - database-reviewer\n   - database-schema-designer\n   - content-engine\n   - content-strategy\n   - market-intelligence\n   - performance-optimizer\n   - documentation-lookup\n   - playwright-pro\n   - shadcn-expert\n   - ui-design-system\n   - ui-ux-pro-max\n   - others in the general capability layer\n\n2. **AHV DTLX domain-specific agents**\n   - ahv-dtlx-architect\n   - ahv-dtlx-agile\n   - ahv-dtlx-be\n   - ahv-dtlx-fe\n   - ahv-dtlx-qa\n   - ahv-dtlx-review\n   - ahv-dtlx-devops\n   - ahv-dtlx-db-schema\n   - ahv-dtlx-security\n   - ahv-dtlx-senior-security\n   - ahv-dtlx-ui-design\n   - ahv-dtlx-ui-ux\n   - ahv-dtlx-perf\n   - ahv-dtlx-prompt\n   - ahv-dtlx-harness\n   - ahv-dtlx-docs\n   - ahv-dtlx-epic\n   - ahv-dtlx-product-strategy\n   - ahv-dtlx-content-engine\n   - ahv-dtlx-content-strategy\n   - ahv-dtlx-market\n   - ahv-dtlx-standards\n   - ahv-dtlx-shadcn\n   - ahv-dtlx-stitch\n   - ahv-dtlx-playwright\n   - ahv-dtlx-seo\n   - and adjacent ecosystem-specific variants\n\n3. **Control layer**\n   - master-orchestrator\n   - prompt-optimizer (used as a workflow gate)\n   - potentially planner / harness-optimizer depending on task class","newText":"## Current inventory snapshot\n\n### Observed ecosystem shape\nThe current ecosystem is composed of **two distinct agent populations**:\n\n**1. System / Generic Agents — 38 agents**\nThese agents provide reusable capability across any project. They are the platform backbone and are named generically (e.g., `senior-frontend`, `prompt-optimizer`, `database-schema-designer`).\n\nFull list of system agents (38):\n- agile-product-owner\n- ai-seo\n- article-writing\n- clean-code\n- code-reviewer\n- coding-standards\n- content-engine\n- content-strategy\n- database-reviewer\n- database-schema-designer\n- deep-research\n- documentation-lookup\n- epic-design\n- harness-optimizer\n- market-intelligence\n- master-orchestrator\n- performance-optimizer\n- planner\n- playwright-pro\n- product-marketing-context\n- product-strategy\n- prompt-optimizer\n- realistic-seeder\n- refactor-cleaner\n- security-reviewer\n- senior-architect\n- senior-backend\n- senior-devops\n- senior-frontend\n- senior-qa\n- senior-security\n- seo-audit\n- shadcn-expert\n- stitch-design\n- stitch-loop\n- typescript-reviewer\n- ui-design-system\n- ui-ux-pro-max\n\n**2. AHV DTLX Project-Specific Sessions — 27 agents**\nThese agents were created as dedicated sessions for the AHV DTLX project. They carry project context and domain knowledge specific to DTLX. They are prefixed `ahv-dtlx-` to indicate project ownership.\n\nFull list of DTLX project agents (27):\n- ahv-dtlx-agile\n- ahv-dtlx-architect\n- ahv-dtlx-be\n- ahv-dtlx-clean\n- ahv-dtlx-content-engine\n- ahv-dtlx-content-strategy\n- ahv-dtlx-db-schema\n- ahv-dtlx-devops\n- ahv-dtlx-docs\n- ahv-dtlx-epic\n- ahv-dtlx-fe\n- ahv-dtlx-harness\n- ahv-dtlx-market\n- ahv-dtlx-perf\n- ahv-dtlx-playwright\n- ahv-dtlx-product-strategy\n- ahv-dtlx-prompt\n- ahv-dtlx-qa\n- ahv-dtlx-review\n- ahv-dtlx-security\n- ahv-dtlx-senior-security\n- ahv-dtlx-seo\n- ahv-dtlx-shadcn\n- ahv-dtlx-standards\n- ahv-dtlx-stitch\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-design\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-ux\n\n**Total: 65 agents** (38 system + 27 project-specific)\n\n**3. Control layer**\n- master-orchestrator — primary orchestrator\n- prompt-optimizer — intake and clarification gate\n- planner — task decomposition and sequencing support"}]}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":240,"output":1460,"cacheRead":152336,"cacheWrite":1357,"totalTokens":155393,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776927569534,"responseId":"0638f65323236a67542aa63ae2300a48"}}
{"type":"message","id":"7f39628b","parentId":"4bc295eb","timestamp":"2026-04-23T06:59:49.791Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_42ndvo73w5lg_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"edit\",\n  \"error\": \"Could not find the exact text in /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/02-agent-taxonomy-and-inventory.md. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\\nCurrent file contents:\\n# Agent Taxonomy and Inventory\\n\\n## Purpose\\nThis document defines the classification model for the current multi-agent ecosystem and provides the basis for architecture, governance, workflow design, and future scaling.\\n\\n## Taxonomy Model\\nThe current ecosystem should be classified into four primary layers.\\n\\n## Layer 1 — Control Agents\\nThese agents are responsible for intake, clarification, orchestration, routing, and consolidation.\\n\\n### Characteristics\\n- interact closest to the user or parent request\\n- decide whether specialist delegation is needed\\n- manage sequencing and synthesis\\n- enforce confirmation and workflow gates\\n\\n### Current examples\\n- `master-orchestrator`\\n- `prompt-optimizer`\\n- `planner` (where used as coordination support)\\n- `harness-optimizer` (when operating as an orchestrati\\n... (truncated)\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"edit","error":"Could not find the exact text in /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/02-agent-taxonomy-and-inventory.md. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\nCurrent file contents:\n# Agent Taxonomy and Inventory\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the classification model for the current multi-agent ecosystem and provides the basis for architecture, governance, workflow design, and future scaling.\n\n## Taxonomy Model\nThe current ecosystem should be classified into four primary layers.\n\n## Layer 1 — Control Agents\nThese agents are responsible for intake, clarification, orchestration, routing, and consolidation.\n\n### Characteristics\n- interact closest to the user or parent request\n- decide whether specialist delegation is needed\n- manage sequencing and synthesis\n- enforce confirmation and workflow gates\n\n### Current examples\n- `master-orchestrator`\n- `prompt-optimizer`\n- `planner` (where used as coordination support)\n- `harness-optimizer` (when operating as an orchestrati\n... (truncated)"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776927589784}}
{"type":"message","id":"736cba7e","parentId":"7f39628b","timestamp":"2026-04-23T07:00:22.528Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file content has been reformatted. Let me rewrite the entire file with the correct agent counts.","thinkingSignature":"41017a8e02464612c726ddc596e7dd8625b4c3682e7bc8fa3f9ca1a62999dc3a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5qmfamcsmhy0_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/docs/02-agent-taxonomy-and-inventory.md","content":"# Agent Taxonomy and Inventory\n\n## Purpose\nThis document defines the classification model for the current multi-agent ecosystem and provides the basis for architecture, governance, workflow design, and future scaling.\n\n## Current Ecosystem Composition\n\nThe ecosystem is composed of two distinct agent populations:\n\n### Population 1 — System / Generic Agents: 38 agents\nThese agents provide reusable capability across any project. They are the platform backbone and are named generically.\n\nFull list:\n- agile-product-owner\n- ai-seo\n- article-writing\n- clean-code\n- code-reviewer\n- coding-standards\n- content-engine\n- content-strategy\n- database-reviewer\n- database-schema-designer\n- deep-research\n- documentation-lookup\n- epic-design\n- harness-optimizer\n- market-intelligence\n- master-orchestrator\n- performance-optimizer\n- planner\n- playwright-pro\n- product-marketing-context\n- product-strategy\n- prompt-optimizer\n- realistic-seeder\n- refactor-cleaner\n- security-reviewer\n- senior-architect\n- senior-backend\n- senior-devops\n- senior-frontend\n- senior-qa\n- senior-security\n- seo-audit\n- shadcn-expert\n- stitch-design\n- stitch-loop\n- typescript-reviewer\n- ui-design-system\n- ui-ux-pro-max\n\n### Population 2 — AHV DTLX Project-Specific Sessions: 27 agents\nThese agents were created as dedicated sessions for the AHV DTLX project. They carry project context and domain knowledge specific to DTLX. They are prefixed `ahv-dtlx-` to indicate project ownership.\n\nFull list:\n- ahv-dtlx-agile\n- ahv-dtlx-architect\n- ahv-dtlx-be\n- ahv-dtlx-clean\n- ahv-dtlx-content-engine\n- ahv-dtlx-content-strategy\n- ahv-dtlx-db-schema\n- ahv-dtlx-devops\n- ahv-dtlx-docs\n- ahv-dtlx-epic\n- ahv-dtlx-fe\n- ahv-dtlx-harness\n- ahv-dtlx-market\n- ahv-dtlx-perf\n- ahv-dtlx-playwright\n- ahv-dtlx-product-strategy\n- ahv-dtlx-prompt\n- ahv-dtlx-qa\n- ahv-dtlx-review\n- ahv-dtlx-security\n- ahv-dtlx-senior-security\n- ahv-dtlx-seo\n- ahv-dtlx-shadcn\n- ahv-dtlx-standards\n- ahv-dtlx-stitch\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-design\n- ahv-dtlx-ui-ux\n\n**Total: 65 agents** (38 system + 27 project-specific)\n\n---\n\n## Taxonomy Model\n\n### Layer 1 — Control Agents\nThese agents are responsible for intake, clarification, orchestration, routing, and consolidation.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- interact closest to the user or parent request\n- decide whether specialist delegation is needed\n- manage sequencing and synthesis\n- enforce confirmation and workflow gates\n\n**Current examples:**\n- `master-orchestrator`\n- `prompt-optimizer`\n- `planner` (where used as coordination support)\n- `harness-optimizer` (when operating as an orchestration optimization control role)\n\n**Notes:** This layer is strategically critical. It should remain small, highly reliable, and tightly governed.\n\n### Layer 2 — Reusable Capability Agents\nThese agents provide portable specialist expertise that should be reusable across multiple projects.\n\n#### Capability Clusters\n\n**Engineering:**\n- `senior-frontend`\n- `senior-backend`\n- `senior-architect`\n- `typescript-reviewer`\n- `code-reviewer`\n- `clean-code`\n- `coding-standards`\n- `refactor-cleaner`\n\n**Quality and Security:**\n- `senior-qa`\n- `security-reviewer`\n- `senior-security`\n- `performance-optimizer`\n- `database-reviewer`\n- `database-schema-designer`\n\n**Product, Research, and Strategy:**\n- `agile-product-owner`\n- `product-strategy`\n- `market-intelligence`\n- `deep-research`\n\n**Content and Communication:**\n- `content-engine`\n- `content-strategy`\n- `article-writing`\n- `documentation-lookup`\n- `ai-seo`\n- `seo-audit`\n\n**Design and Experience:**\n- `ui-design-system`\n- `ui-ux-pro-max`\n- `epic-design`\n- `stitch-design`\n- `stitch-loop`\n- `playwright-pro`\n- `shadcn-expert`\n\n**Operational / Utility:**\n- `realistic-seeder`\n- `planner`\n- `harness-optimizer`\n- `product-marketing-context`\n\n### Layer 3 — Project-Specific Agents (DTLX)\nThese agents are tuned for the AHV DTLX domain. They are prefixed `ahv-dtlx-` and carry project context that generic agents may lack. They are project-aligned specialist sessions.\n\n**Product / Planning:**\n- `ahv-dtlx-agile`\n- `ahv-dtlx-epic`\n- `ahv-dtlx-product-strategy`\n- `ahv-dtlx-market`\n\n**Engineering:**\n- `ahv-dtlx-fe`\n- `ahv-dtlx-be`\n- `ahv-dtlx-architect`\n- `ahv-dtlx-db-schema`\n- `ahv-dtlx-devops`\n- `ahv-dtlx-standards`\n- `ahv-dtlx-clean`\n- `ahv-dtlx-review`\n- `ahv-dtlx-perf`\n- `ahv-dtlx-harness`\n\n**Quality / Security:**\n- `ahv-dtlx-qa`\n- `ahv-dtlx-security`\n- `ahv-dtlx-senior-security`\n- `ahv-dtlx-playwright`\n\n**Design / UX:**\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-design`\n- `ahv-dtlx-ui-ux`\n- `ahv-dtlx-shadcn`\n- `ahv-dtlx-stitch`\n\n**Content / Documentation / Discovery:**\n- `ahv-dtlx-docs`\n- `ahv-dtlx-content-engine`\n- `ahv-dtlx-content-strategy`\n- `ahv-dtlx-seo`\n- `ahv-dtlx-prompt`\n\n**Notes:** This layer gives the ecosystem project relevance. It also introduces overlap risk if role boundaries between project agents and system agents are not clearly documented.\n\n### Layer 4 — Temporary or Situation-Specific Agents\nThis layer should include agents created for a temporary initiative, migration, experiment, or narrow scope.\n\n**Why formalizing this layer matters:** Without a temporary-agent classification, the ecosystem tends to accumulate agents without a retirement model, which increases confusion and maintenance overhead.\n\n---\n\n## Classification Principles\nTo reduce future ambiguity, each agent should explicitly declare:\n1. **Population** — system / generic or project / DTLX-specific\n2. **Layer** — control / reusable / domain / temporary\n3. **Capability cluster**\n4. **Reusable or project-specific status**\n5. **Expected inputs**\n6. **Expected outputs**\n7. **Escalation targets**\n8. **Lifecycle status** — draft / active / limited / deprecated\n\n---\n\n## Inventory Observations\n\n### Observation 1 — Clear two-population structure\nThe ecosystem naturally separates into system/generic agents and project-specific DTLX agents. This is intentional and should be preserved.\n\n### Observation 2 — Strong coverage\nThe ecosystem already covers most major internal operating functions needed for AI-assisted delivery.\n\n### Observation 3 — Overlap risk between populations\nSeveral areas have both a generic agent and a DTLX-specific variant but no authoritative boundary definition. For example:\n- `code-reviewer` vs `ahv-dtlx-review`\n- `database-schema-designer` vs `ahv-dtlx-db-schema`\n- `ui-design-system` vs `ahv-dtlx-ui-design`\n- `senior-frontend` vs `ahv-dtlx-fe`\n\nThis creates confusion about when to use which.\n\n### Observation 4 — Missing authoritative registry\nThere is no single source of truth listing all 65 agents, their population, status, maturity, and when they should be used.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Registry Fields\nA formal registry should include at minimum:\n- Agent Name\n- Population (System / DTLX-Specific)\n- Layer\n- Capability Cluster\n- Scope\n- Maturity Level\n- Lifecycle Status (Draft / Active / Limited / Deprecated)\n\n---\n\n## Immediate Recommendations\n1. Create a canonical agent registry covering all 65 agents\n2. Assign each agent to one taxonomy layer and population\n3. Define boundary rules between system and DTLX-specific agents\n4. Add lifecycle status to every agent\n5. Standardize AGENTS.md structure across the ecosystem\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":322,"output":1955,"cacheRead":152555,"cacheWrite":2779,"totalTokens":157611,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776927589810,"responseId":"0638f667c1287139846de1cb9b177fef"}}
